<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate cost per wear?", answer: "Divide the purchase price by the estimated number of times you will wear the item. For example, a $200 jacket worn 100 times costs $2.00 per wear. A $50 jacket worn only 10 times costs $5.00 per wear, making the expensive jacket the better value in this scenario." },
  { question: "What is a good cost per wear?", answer: "A good target is under $1 per wear for everyday basics like jeans, t-shirts, and shoes. For special occasion items, under $5-10 per wear is reasonable. Workwear should aim for under $2-3 per wear. The lower the cost per wear, the better the value. Items you wear frequently always have a lower cost per wear." },
  { question: "Is expensive clothing always a better value per wear?", answer: "Not always, but often. Higher-quality clothing tends to last longer and maintain its appearance through more wears and washes, resulting in a lower cost per wear. However, trendy items worn only a few times have a high cost per wear regardless of price. The key factor is how often you actually wear the item, not just its durability." },
  { question: "How do I estimate the number of wears for an item?", answer: "Consider how often you would wear the item per week and for how many years. A pair of jeans worn twice a week for 3 years is 312 wears. A winter coat worn daily for 4 months annually over 5 years is about 600 wears. A formal dress worn 4 times a year for 5 years is 20 wears. Be realistic about your habits." },
  { question: "Should I consider resale value in cost per wear?", answer: "Yes. If you plan to resell an item, subtract the expected resale price from the purchase price before calculating cost per wear. A $300 handbag resold for $150 has an effective cost of $150. If you carry it 200 times, the adjusted cost per wear is $0.75 instead of $1.50." }
]) %>

